{"files": {"SKILL.md": "# Bench Engineer's Manual\n\nA practical handbook for landing a coded change inside someone else's working tree.\n\n## Survey first\n\nBefore any edit, look for the layout document the project ships \u2014 a posted layout, an index, a README that names paths and the test command. The published version is current; recall is not. Reads of guessed paths in the same call as the layout document are wasted budget \u2014 the layout document's job is to remove the guessing.\n\n## Honour the contract\n\nThe request is the spec. Implement exactly what it asks for. Files outside what it names stay untouched \u2014 including renames, reformats, and refactors. Doing more than asked is a regression, not a bonus.\n\n## Branching and commits\n\nBefore any edit on an existing repo, switch onto a fresh branch named after the request:\n\n```\ngit checkout -b <request-branch>\n```\n\nIf earlier request-branches are present, branch from the most recent one. Branching from the default re-introduces work already shipped on a prior request.\n\nFor a fresh tree, configure committer identity and lay down a baseline commit before any task work \u2014 without identity the commit fails silently:\n\n```\ngit config user.name <name>\ngit config user.email <email>\necho \"*.pyc\" > .gitignore && git add .gitignore && git commit -m 'scaffold'\ngit checkout -b <request-branch>\n```\n\nThe first useful change becomes a commit the moment it touches disk \u2014 ahead of running the test suite. The suite informs the *next* commit. Uncommitted work is fragile.\n\nStage by exact path:\n\n```\ngit add src/file.py\n```\n\nBulk staging (`-A`, `.`) drags caches, build outputs, editor backups, and agent scratch files into the diff. Reviewers reject those.\n\nOne commit per working unit with a short message. No history rewrites \u2014 no amend, no rebase, no squash; they erase context the next reader would have used.\n\n## File transport \u2014 bytes verbatim\n\nFor multi-line writes, the default is author the file in your own scratch space and ship the bytes across:\n\n```\nscp <local_file> <remote>:<remote_path>\n```\n\n`scp` is byte-verbatim. Heredocs corrupt triple-quoted strings, backticks, and `$` in ways that take longer to debug than the change itself. Do not begin with a heredoc and \"fix it later.\"\n\nWhere `scp` is unavailable, the fallback is a tiny Python helper that holds the payload in a triple-quoted string and writes it.\n\nFor a one-byte edit \u2014 flipping an operator, swapping a constant, renaming an identifier \u2014 an in-place stream-edit on the remote is the surgical instrument:\n\n```\nsed -i 's/old/new/' <remote_path>\n```\n\nDo not reupload an entire file to change one byte.\n\n## Reads and writes \u2014 order with care\n\nIndependent reads belong in a single tool call that lists every path at once. A read counts as independent only if its target path is known before any earlier read returns. If the second read's path is computed from the first read's content, they cannot share a call.\n\nWrites go the other way: one write, then re-inspect what the write produced, then the next. Concurrent writes are difficult to untangle on failure.\n\nDo not pair a read of the layout file with reads of paths you guessed. The layout file's purpose is to remove that.\n\n## Run the tests, read the output\n\nThe test runner is the only authority that matters for a coded change. Every other signal \u2014 your reading of the diff, the request's framing, your sense that it \"should work\" \u2014 is provisional until the runner agrees.\n\nRun the suite after each substantive change. Read the output line by line, not the exit code alone. A failing case is concrete; a green log is provisional until you have read every line you expected to see green. The failure message and the assertion line together specify the missing behaviour.\n\nWhen a case fails, the smallest correct fix is preferable to a sweeping rewrite. Preserve passing cases \u2014 they are someone's prior work and a test that flips green-to-red anywhere is a regression.\n\n## Anti-patterns that ship subtly broken code\n\nImplementations that look right but fail strict inputs share a shape \u2014 they handle the typical case and miss the edge of the input space. Stay alert to these shapes:\n\n- **Threshold and capacity edges.** When a rule blocks \"after N events\" or includes \"the first M items,\" decide explicitly whether the Nth is the last allowed or the first blocked, and write the comparison to that decision.\n- **Window endpoints.** Ranges, slices, time intervals \u2014 both ends matter. The convention is rarely symmetric; choose one and apply it everywhere in the change.\n- **Identity vs canonical form for keys.** When deduplicating or grouping, two values \"equal in some sense\" must be compared in canonical form, not by identity. Lowercase strings, sort lists, normalise dicts before keying.\n- **Time and zone arithmetic.** Wall-clock to wall-clock conversion routes through a zone-aware library, not raw offset arithmetic.\n- **Named access over positional access.** When the input is structured, prefer access by name over access by index. Position drifts when the producer reorders fields.\n- **Indexing-base conversions.** When two systems use different bases, convert exactly once at the boundary and validate the result. Mixed bases inside a function are how off-by-ones reach production.\n\nRecognise the shape; do not memorise a recipe. Stricter cases pressure-test the *shape* of the fix, not the operator you chose.\n\n## Durable notes\n\nIf a notebook directory exists in the working area, treat it as a journal that survives across runs. A useful structure when the directory is writable:\n\n- one file naming the project's facts: directory layout, test command, build command \u2014 one line each\n- one file naming defect categories encountered: `<failing case or symptom> \u2014 <root cause> \u2014 <fix>`\n- one file naming environment quirks and the workaround that ended up working\n\nHabits for the journal:\n\n1. A surprise becomes one line in the notebook the moment it surfaces \u2014 deferring the write loses it.\n2. The defect file accepts only entries whose fix has been confirmed by a passing run. Future readers treat each line as fact; an unverified line corrupts whoever comes next.\n3. One line per fact. Update in place; never duplicate.\n4. When live observation contradicts a stored line, the stored line is replaced.\n5. Skip generic language knowledge, today's revision, today's path \u2014 anything the version control history could re-derive.\n\nWhen a request begins, read the journal first. If the request smells like a recurrence \u2014 same defect category, same surface area, same symptom \u2014 start from the earlier resolution rather than re-deriving from scratch. Cite the prior commit identifier in your first message so the trace is legible.\n\n## When the request asks for a written diagnosis\n\nA request for an after-action note, a written diagnosis, or documentation of a fault category lives in the notebook directory, not the repository \u2014 it is not committed.\n\nTo be useful, such a write-up must include:\n- the defect category named in plain language\n- the specific failing case identifiers from the prior runs' result files (quoted exactly as the runner emitted them)\n- a short description of the underlying mistake\n- a code excerpt from the resolving commit on the prior request branch (retrieved with `git show` against that branch's path)\n\nA generic write-up that could apply to any defect in the domain is not useful. Specifics make it functional for the next person.\n\n## Exit cleanly\n\nAct, do not narrate. A prose summary is not a deliverable; only the landed commits count.\n\nA small landed change beats an elegant uncommitted draft. A commit on the right branch with the obvious cases passing is the floor; covering the strict edge cases is the ceiling. Reach the floor first, then add coverage.\n"}, "schema_version": 1}